<br>
I want to make clear that I do not mind porting. That is part of my job and I love having the freedom and the ability to do so. <br>
<br>
On that note I will ask people to try to be a little thoughtful to druids/wizzies when asking for ports. Here are some good tips to go by.<br>
<br>
1. If you need a port for a raid please send a tell to a druid or wizard if you dont get a response wait a few minutes we may be zoning. We do that alot. If you get a response then make every effort to get to the nearest druid circle/wizard spire. Many times we have alot of people to port and having to run all over can delay the start of a raid unnecessarily. <br>
<br>
2. If its a raid that the time has been posted and you are unable to come on time please dont ask guild porters to leave raid until you have exhausted the possibility of getting one on your own. Many times druids are the main healer in a group and many times as that we are also group leaders. Its putting a whole group at risk by leaving. <br>
<br>
3. Post raid-most druids and wizzys disband from groups to form port groups after a raid to get everyone out safely. Saves time if you are paying attention to who has openings for a port out and send a tell to that person. <br>
<br>
4. I cant speak for others where porting outside raid circumstances but I dont mind porting those that need it. I will do my best to do so if I have the time. Many times when I am at guild functions I am soloing so I will be able to get away. On that note when you ask any druid or wizard to port you when they are in a different zone its nice to have you waiting at the appropriate circle or spire. In the end it will save both time because we dont have to run all over looking.<br>
<br>
Launie Windancer<br>
55 Preserver<br>
Odysseys<br>
Xev<br>
